Data Engineering Fundamentals — Study Notes
Personal study notes on core data engineering concepts, covering the data engineering lifecycle, storage paradigms, and the skill set required of a data engineer.
1. What Is Data Engineering?
Data engineering is the development, implementation, and maintenance of systems and processes that take in raw data and produce high-quality, consistent information that supports downstream use cases — such as analysis and machine learning.
Put another way: data engineering is the intersection of security, data management/DataOps, data architecture, orchestration, and software engineering.
2. Why Data Engineering Is Complex
•	Data engineering has to handle a lot of complex, moving parts, and must constantly optimize along several competing axes: 
o	Cost
o	Agility
o	Scalability
o	Simplicity
o	Reuse
o	Interoperability
•	Modern tools considerably abstract and simplify workflows compared to earlier generations of data infrastructure.
•	As a result, data engineers today focus less on building everything from scratch and more on balancing the simplest, most cost-effective, best-of-breed service that delivers value to the business.
•	Data engineering is also expected to create agile data architecture — systems that can evolve as new trends and technologies emerge, rather than static, brittle pipelines.

3. Data Maturity and Data Engineering
•	Data maturity is the progression of an organization toward higher data utilization.
•	As data maturity increases, the demands placed on the data engineering function (and its architecture) grow correspondingly.
4. The Data Engineering Lifecycle
The data engineering lifecycle describes how a data engineer manages the movement of data — from raw data in source systems to serving data for downstream use cases such as analytics or machine learning.
Lifecycle stages:
Generation → Ingestion → Transformation → Serving → Storage
Storage underlies the entire lifecycle, not just one stage in it.
Undercurrents (cross-cutting concerns)
These run underneath every stage of the lifecycle:
•	Security
•	Data management (DataOps)
•	Data architecture
•	Orchestration
•	Software engineering
5. Storage Paradigms
Concept	Description
Data Warehouse	Structured data only (e.g. CSV, tabular formats)
Data Lake	Stores raw data, structured and unstructured
Lakehouse	Hybrid — combines structured and unstructured data (e.g. Snowflake, Databricks)
Tools by Lifecycle Stage
Stage	Example Tools
Ingestion	Cloud Dataflow
Transformation	Dataprep
Serving	Analytics, ML/Learning, Reverse ETL
Storage	Snowflake, Databricks

6. Source Systems & Ingestion
•	Ingestion tooling: commonly built with Python
•	Ingestion patterns: 
o	Batch — periodic, scheduled loads
o	Streaming — continuous, real-time ingestion (e.g. Kafka)
7. Transformation
•	OLTP (Online Transaction Processing) — optimized for fast, transactional read/write (source systems)
•	OLAP (Online Analytical Processing) — optimized for complex queries and analysis (warehouses)
8. The Data Science Hierarchy of Needs
This pyramid (based on Monica Rogati's "Data Science Hierarchy of Needs") splits responsibility between data engineering (bottom three levels) and data science (top two levels):
              ▲
             / \
            / AI/ML \          ─┐
           /---------\           ├─ Data Science
          / Analytics  \        ─┘
         /--------------\
        / Aggregate/Label \    ─┐
       /--------------------\    │
      /  Store / Move / Process \ ├─ Data Engineering
     /------------------------------\  │
    /   Collect (instrument, log,  \  ─┘
   /    sensors, external, user-     \
  /     generated content)             \
 /--------------------------------------\
From the base up:
1.	Collect — instrumentation, logging, sensors, external data, user-generated content (Data Engineering)
2.	Store / Move / Process — reliable data flow and infrastructure (Data Engineering)
3.	Aggregate / Label — cleaning, feature prep, exploratory data analysis (Data Engineering)
4.	Analytics — metrics, A/B testing, reporting (Data Science)
5.	AI / ML — the top of the pyramid (Data Science)
Although many data scientists are eager to build and tune ML models, an estimated 70–80% of their time is actually spent in the bottom three layers — gathering, cleaning, and processing data — with only a small slice going to analysis and ML itself. Rogati's point: companies need to build a solid data foundation (i.e. invest in data engineering) before the top of the pyramid is worth pursuing.
